'''Lee C. Rogers''' (born February 27, 1978) is an American [[podiatrist]] from [[Simi Valley, California]].  He is most known for his work at [[Valley Presbyterian Hospital]] in Van Nuys preventing amputations in diabetes and [[Charcot arthropathy|Charcot foot]].  He is a Democratic candidate for US Congress in [[United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2012|California's 25th district]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Holt|first=Jim|title=McKeon, Rogers count their contributors|url=http://www.the-signal.com/archives/59242/|newspaper=The Santa Clarita Valley Signal|date=February 2, 2012}}</ref>

==Biography==
===Early life and education===
Rogers was born in [[Elgin, Illinois]] to George Robert and Madelynn Jean Rogers and moved to [[Gallatin, Missouri]] at a young age.  He attended primary and secondary school in Gallatin.  He was awarded the [[Congress Bundestag Youth Exchange]] scholarship and spent his senior year in [[Uetersen]], Germany.

Rogers attended [[Truman State University]] in [[Kirksville, Missouri]] from 1996–2000.  He graduated with a [[Doctor of Podiatric Medicine]] (DPM) from [[Des Moines University]] College of Podiatric Medicine in 2004 where he was president of the student body.  He completed a residency in foot surgery at [[Saint Vincent's Catholic Medical Center]] in New York, NY and then later a fellowship in limb salvage and research with [[David G. Armstrong]] at [[Rosalind Franklin University of Medicine and Science]] in North Chicago, IL.

===Des Moines===
Following his fellowship, Rogers founded and directed the Amputation Prevention Center at Broadlawns Medical Center in Des Moines, Iowa.  While in Iowa, Rogers described the 6 steps to preventing amputations and published a reduction in major amputations by 72%.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rogers|first=LC|coauthors=Bevilacqua, NJ|title=Organized programs to prevent lower-extremity amputations.|journal=Journal of the American Podiatric Medical Association|year=2010|month=March-April|volume=100|issue=2|pages=101-4|pmid=20237360|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed?term=Organized%20programs%20to%20reduce%20lower-extremity%20amputations}}</ref>  Rogers won first place for outstanding research from the [[American Podiatric Medical Association]] (APMA) in 2007 for mesenchymal stem cell research on wounds<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rogers|first=LC|coauthors=Bevilacqua, NJ; Armstrong, DG|title=The use of marrow-derived stem cells to accelerate healing in chronic wounds.|journal=International Wound Journal|year=2008|month=March|volume=5|issue=1|pages=20-5|pmid=18179555|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18179555}}</ref> and 2009 for hi-tech wound measurement techniques.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rogers|first=LC|coauthors=Bevilacqua, NJ; Armstrong, DG; Andros, G|title=Digital planimetry results in more accurate wound measurements: a comparison to standard ruler measurements.|journal=Journal of Diabetes Science and Technology|year=2010|month=July|volume=4|issue=4|pages=799-802|pmid=20663440|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2909508/?tool=pubmed}}</ref> He proposed simple measures to reduce costs of amputations in the healthcare system.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rogers|first=LC|coauthors=Lavery, LA; Armstrong, DG|title=The right to bear legs--an amendment to healthcare: how preventing amputations can save billions for the US Health-care System.|journal=Journal of the American Podiatric Medical Association|year=2008|month=March-April|volume=98|issue=2|pages=166-8|pmid=18348977|url=http://www.japmaonline.org/content/98/2/166.citation}}</ref>

===Los Angeles, California===
Rogers was recruited to [[Valley Presbyterian Hospital]] by George Andros, MD, a renown vascular surgeon, to co-create the Amputation Prevention Center in Los Angeles.  The doctors created an 8,000 square foot inpatient and outpatient specialty center which greatly improved upon limb salvage and wound healing rates.<ref name="autogenerated1"/>  Rogers became co-director of the Global Diabetic Foot Conference (DFCon), an annual conference in [[Hollywood, California]] with 1000 participants from all 50 states and 40 different countries.  In 2009, he became Chair of the Foot Care Council of the [[American Diabetes Association]] and his most noted accomplishment was the creation of consensus guidelines for the treatment of Charcot foot which took place at the [[Pitié-Salpêtrière Hospital]] in Paris, France.  The guidelines were jointly published in the Journal of the American Podiatric Medical Association<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rogers|first=LC|coauthors=Frykberg, RG; Armstrong, DG; Boulton, AJ; Edmonds, M; Van, GH; Hartemann, A; Game, F; Jeffcoate, W; Jirkovska, A; Jude, E; Morbach, S; Morrison, WB; Pinzur, M; Pitocco, D; Sanders, L; Wukich, DK; Uccioli, L|title=The Charcot foot in diabetes.|journal=Journal of the American Podiatric Medical Association|year=2011|month=September-October|volume=101|issue=5|pages=437-46|pmid=21957276|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21957276}}</ref> and Diabetes Care.<ref name="autogenerated2"/> He received the Rising Star Award from the APMA in 2011 for outstanding national accomplishments.  He is an Assistant Professor of [[Podiatry]] at [[Western University of Health Sciences]] in Pomona, California.

===Political endeavors===
Rogers announced his candidacy for US Congress from [[California's 25th congressional district|California’s 25th district]] in August 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-signal.com/section/36/article/49237/ |title=Doctor says he's running for Congress |publisher=The Santa Clarita Valley Signal |date=August 8, 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-17}}</ref>

Rogers or his work has been quoted in the ''Wall Street Journal'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilde |first=Anna |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704657304575540440173772102.html |title=Physician Panel Prescribes the Fees Paid by Medicare |publisher=Wall Street Journal |date=October 26, 2010 |accessdate=2011-10-17}}</ref> ''U.S. News & World Report'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://health.usnews.com/health-news/family-health/diabetes/articles/2008/01/28/preventing-foot-ulcers-caused-by-diabetes |title=Preventing Foot Ulcers Caused By Diabetes |publisher=US News and World Report |date=2008-01-28 |accessdate=2011-10-17}}</ref> the ''Washington Post'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Tamura|first=Leslie|title=Physicians use photos from patients' cellphones to deliver 'mobile health'|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/08/30/AR2010083003939_pf.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=August 31, 2010}}</ref> CBS News,<ref>{{cite web|last=Freeman|first=David W.|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504763_162-20074042-10391704.html |title=Dog chews off toe of diabetic woman as she sleeps |publisher=CBS News |date=June 24, 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-17}}</ref> and many medical specialty magazines.  He has authored over 100 articles and book chapters.

